{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643986"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:00:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:00:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18026"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18026"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.68,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114559"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10740"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96560"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9901"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27727"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114559"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman undergoes pulmonary function testing. The respiratory physiologist explains to her the different lung volumes being measured.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes residual volume?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Volume of air remaining after normal expiration","Volume of air remaining in lungs after maximal expiration","Volume of air exhaled during forced expiration","Volume of air inhaled during maximal inspiration","Volume of air inhaled during normal breathing"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of air remaining in lungs after maximal expiration\u003C/strong\u003E correctly defines residual volume. This volume cannot be exhaled and therefore cannot be measured directly by spirometry. It serves an important physiological function by preventing complete alveolar collapse and maintaining gas exchange throughout the respiratory cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of air inhaled during normal breathing\u003C/strong\u003E describes tidal volume, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Evolume of air exhaled during forced expiration\u003C/strong\u003E describes forced expiratory volume. \u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of air remaining after normal expiration\u003C/strong\u003E describes functional residual capacity, which includes both residual volume and expiratory reserve volume, and \u003Cstrong\u003Evolume of air inhaled during maximal inspiration\u003C/strong\u003E describes inspiratory capacity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResidual volume can only be measured indirectly using techniques such as helium dilution or body plethysmography.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Residual volume is the volume of air remaining in the lungs after maximal expiration.","Residual volume cannot be measured by spirometry as it cannot be exhaled.","Residual volume prevents alveolar collapse and maintains gas exchange during breathing cycles."],"references":["West JB, Luks AM. West\u2019s respiratory physiology: the essentials. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer; 2015. Chapter 2; pg. 16.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96560"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"q